April World Language Newsletter Celebrates Ramadan, Autism Awareness and the Earth April is a month to celebrate Ramadan, autism awareness and our Earth. The latest World Language newsletter presents an overview of Ramadan and the personal experiences of some of our high school's Muslim students. It also includes articles that focus on ways to live a sustainable life, suggestions for new sources of energy, information on the climate refugee crisis, the history of American Sign Language and autism awareness in the Hispanic community. We hope you enjoy this monthâ€™s edition and apply some of the suggestions offered by our students to live a more sustainable life and protect our environment. https://www.deerparkschools.org/news/article.aspx?id=151405:=:https://www.deerparkschools.org/news/story.aspx?id=151405

Now playing a new Latino USA podcast! LISTEN HERE: https://bit.ly/lusaborder3:=:https://www.latinousa.org/2022/03/11/themovingborderpartthree/ After two years, Maria Hinojosa returns to Mexicoâ€™s southern border for the latest episode of the award-winning series "The Moving Border." In 2020, the series revealed how a complex web of policies, created by the United States under the Trump presidency and supported by Mexico's own government, had created a virtually impenetrable policy wall for asylum seekers. This time, the series explores changes â€”or the lack ofâ€” after the first year of the Biden administration, and their effect on migrants who have spent months, sometimes years, trying to make it through Mexico into the U.S. Finding that the demographic of asylum seekers arriving in Mexico has changed, the report shifts even further south, traveling to the DariÃ©n Gap, the jungle at the border between Colombia and Panama, where hundreds of people arrive daily, risking their lives in hopes of making it one step closer to the U.S. LISTEN HERE: bit.ly/lusaborder3:=:https://www.latinousa.org/2022/03/11/themovingborderpartthree/

Now playing a new Latino USA podcast! LISTEN HERE: https://bit.ly/lusaoscars:=:https://www.latinousa.org/2022/03/04/oscars/ 2021 was a big year for Latinos in Hollywood, and now theyâ€™re getting some awards season love. With this yearâ€™s nominations, the Academy Awards are shining a spotlight on some Latino artists, with hit films like "Encanto" and "West Side Story" in the running for some of the eveningâ€™s biggest prizesâ€”and to possibly even make some history. But many critics find it worth asking: is this the kind of representation Latinos and Latinas have been looking for in Hollywood? And after being systematically shut out of the Oscars for nearly a century, is this recognition from the Academy something we should be striving for, anyway? On this episode of Latino USA, Latino and Latina film critics Clayton Davis, Cristina Escobar, and Jack Rico step up to the mic for a roundtable about Latinos in film this past year. Ahead of Hollywoodâ€™s biggest night, they discuss the honors (and snubs) for Latino-led films this awards season. They also talk about the importance of diversity in criticism and push the conversation past the topic of â€œrepresentationâ€ to envision a more inclusive future for Latinos in Hollywood and the film industry as a whole. LISTEN HERE: bit.ly/lusaoscars:=:https://www.latinousa.org/2022/03/04/oscars/

This week, Latino USA presents the first part of Reveal from Reveal from The Center for Investigative Reporting's 3-part series, #AfterAyotzinapa. LISTEN HERE: https://bit.ly/lusaayotzinapa:=:https://www.latinousa.org/2022/01/28/afterayotzinapa/ It has been over seven years since 43 students from the Ayotzinapa Rural Teachersâ€™ College in Guerrero, Mexico, were taken by armed men in the middle of the night. They were never seen again. Their disappearance sparked mass protests, as the 43 became symbols of Mexicoâ€™s unchecked human rights abuses. In recent decades, tens of thousands of people have gone missing in Mexico, and almost no one has been held accountable. The culture of impunity is so ingrained that families often donâ€™t go to police for help, believing theyâ€™re either corrupt or too afraid to investigate. In the first part of a three-part investigation of the Ayotzinapa case, Reveal from The Center for Investigative Reporting's Anayansi Diaz-Cortes and Kate Doyle from the National Security Archive take us inside the investigation into the attack on the students. LISTEN HERE: bit.ly/lusaayotzinapa:=:https://www.latinousa.org/2022/01/28/afterayotzinapa/ For parts two and three, go to the Reveal from The Center for Investigative Reporting's podcast feed.

Now playing a new Latino USA podcast! LISTEN HERE: https://bit.ly/lusatejano:=:https://www.latinousa.org/2022/01/25/veroniquemedrano/ Veronique Medrano is a Tejano and Spanish Country singer from Brownsville, Texas in the Rio Grande Valley. Veronique finds inspiration as an artist from her experiences living on the border, her Mexican-American identity, and her everyday life. On this "How I Made It" segment, Veronique walks us through the origins and diversity of Tejano music, being a woman in a male-dominated industry, and the importance of archiving and preserving the genre for future generations. LISTEN HERE: bit.ly/lusatejano:=:https://www.latinousa.org/2022/01/25/veroniquemedrano/

Now playing a new Latino USA podcast! LISTEN HERE: https://bit.ly/tangoresiste:=:https://www.latinousa.org/2022/01/07/tangoresiste/ While tango is usually pictured as a dance between a white man in an elegant black suit and a white woman in high heels and a tight red dress, the reality of tango goes much deeper. Born in the brothels and dance halls of Buenos Airesâ€™ lower caste, this music and dance are actually rooted in Argentinaâ€™s African and queer subcultures. Before it became the defining music of Argentina, tango was actually condemned by elites, and the Catholic church, which saw it as obscene and transgressive. The danceâ€™s reign was also threatened by the worldwide phenomenon of rock nâ€™ roll and then all but buried by Argentina's Dirty War. When tango began its revival in the 1980s and 90s, a new era of tango artists began challenging rigid norms established in the early half of the 20th century. Breaking from traditional gender roles and shining a light on the Black history of tango, these artists aimed to invoke tangoâ€™s past to make way for a more inclusive future. In this episode, weâ€™ll travel to Argentina and meet three women who will help us to understand the controversial roots of tango and how they are helping to give new life to a dance very much rooted in tradition. LISTEN HERE: bit.ly/tangoresiste:=:https://www.latinousa.org/2022/01/07/tangoresiste/

Now playing a new Latino USA podcast! LISTEN HERE: https://bit.ly/lusastefa:=:https://www.latinousa.org/2021/12/21/stefasoriginstories/ When vocalist, composer and multi-media performance artist STEFA â€”also known as STEFA*â€” takes the stage, it feels like walking through a portal into somewhere that is both past and future. Born and raised in Queens, NY to Colombian immigrant parents, STEFA*â€™s music explores themes such as reconnecting with their ancestors and falling in love under capitalism. On this "How I Made It" segment, Stefa talks about their journey as a multifaceted artist creating their own origin stories as a non-binary, Indigenous person trying to find home in their body. Futuro Media was founded to specifically elevate the voices and perspective of marginalized peoples, and to confront inequities they face. Our staff is committed to reporting on issues of inequality from the perspective of those who experience inequality on a daily basis, and who mostly go unheard. After working in this type of newsroom, our reporters are energized, and motivated to change the face of the journalism industry. "The Latino USA team is a group of inspiring and dedicated journalists doing the important work of elevating stories and issues often left out of mainstream media," said Stephanie Lebow, Latino USA's Director of Engineering and Sound Designer said. "Latino USA gives a platform to underrepresented voices, with heart and authenticity." This is the last week to support the Latino USA Legacy Fund! Since Latino USA first appeared on the air waves 30 years ago, it has become its own cultural institution. Now Maria Hinojosa's voice is one that so many people have heard on their radios week after week. "Latino USA is an institution, part of the fabric of Latino America," said Hector Luis Alamo, Senior Editor at Latino Rebels. "Personally, as a Latino from Chicago, Maria's voice will always remind me of home, especially of my college days and the blossoming of my social consciousness." Help us honor the past of Latino USA, and secure our future. Support the Latino USA Legacy Fund today! Click to Give: https://bit.ly/3M4Ocre:=:https://www.futuromediagroup.org/donate/

History we all should be aware of. â€œJune 19th is Juneteenth, the oldest known U.S. celebration commemorating the end of slavery. The Emancipation Proclamation was on January 1, 1863 and General Order No. 3 was on June 19, 1865. Juneteenth has been observed since 1866, but Dr. Opal Lee championed it into a national holiday. SHADE EQUITY AND CLIMATE CHANGE / SHADE IN LA Artist Highlight: Aleka Corwin. â€œShade in Laâ€ is a public art installation curated by Jolly de Guzman. Arroyo Arts Collective Artists and the Rock Rose Gallery Youth Art Interns explore the themes of climate change, heat, drought, and wildfire, using repurposed umbrellas their canvas. The proposed outdoor installation will address and highlight the issue of shade equity, a problem that disproportionately affects low-income and working-class communities and people of color, who are more likely to work outdoors, rely on public transportation, and live in neighborhoods with a lack of trees and shade. As the climate changes and the planet warms, what was once thought primarily as an aesthetic amenity is increasingly recognized as a way of protecting the public health and wellbeing of marginalized communities. Shade in L.A. is made possible through the generous support of the Los Angeles Department of Cultural Affairs, the Los Angeles County Board of Supervisors through the Los Angeles County Arts Commission and by the California Arts Council, a state agency. This programming is presented in partnership with Avenue 50 Studio, the Los Angeles Center for Urban Natural Resources Sustainability, and the US Forest Service Urban and Community Forestry Program. Arroyo Arts Collective: Established in 1989 as a community organization of artists, writers and performers who live and work in Northeast Los Angeles, the mission of the Arroyo Arts Collective is to develop and present creative events that educate while fostering an awareness of the artistic vitality which exists in northeast Los Angeles. http://arroyoartscollective.org/:=:https://arroyoartscollective.org/ @arroyoartscollective @alekacorwinartist @dearantler @shadeinLA @avenue50studio

Hispanic/Latino Americans increased risk for diabetes can be traced back to a variety of reasons from where your family is from, the presence of certain genes or dietary choices. You can't change where your family is from or your genes, but you can make better food choices. Pair this with incorporating exercise daily and visiting your White-Wilson doctor for regular checkups and the risk of diabetes won't just decrease, so will the risk of heart disease and stroke. #NationalMinorityHealthMonth

While no one is for sure what causes certain ethnic groups to be more prone to diseases like cancer, we do know what steps to take that can reduce the risk of death related to these conditions. First and foremost, make sure you are on top of your recommended screenings. Early detection is the best tool we have to beat cancer and screening is pivotal to that, especially if you're genetic background puts you at a higher risk. If you are concerned about your risk of cancer, talk to your White-Wilson provider about what steps you can take and scheduling a screening with our team of specialists. #NationalMinorityHealthMonth

To schedule an annual wellness exam and screening, call 850.863.8100. #NationalMinorityHealthMonth

Because the symptoms of glaucoma start slowly, many people fail to recognize the onset of the disease until vision becomes noticeably impaired, especially in the peripheral. These eye exams can help ophthalmologists detect glaucoma sooner and mitigate or stop its progression. Dr. Julian Tokarev of the White-Wilson Ophthalmology Clinic specializes in the early diagnosis of glaucoma and the use of interventional treatment methods to help preserve your sight. Washington D.C.,- Each week throughout the month of June, the National Federation of Filipino-American Associations (NaFFAA) will celebrate and recognize the thoughts, stories and accomplishments of its LGBTQI+ leaders in honor of Pride Month. Through the â€œNational Advocacyâ€ pillar of empowerment, NaFFAA calls for a more inclusive Filipino-American community and be an example of showing love and intolerance against all forms of hate crimes toward the LGBTQI+ community. Recent studies show that 40% of AAPI LGBTQI+ youths have considered suicide in the last year. A survey from the Trevor Project found that 40 percent of LGBTQI+ youths who are Asian American or Pacific Islander, or AAPI, have seriously considered suicide in the past year. Pacific Islander/Native Hawaiian youths experienced the highest rate, at 49 percent, followed by Korean American youths, at 47 percent, and Filipino American youths, at 41 percent. For many Filipino Americans, coming out is a lifelong process that can require a different approach because of cultural norms or traditions that emphasize duty to family and community. â€œWe celebrate each member of our Filipino community. We are proud of the unique talents, perspectives, and offerings each of you provides to make our 4 million strong Filipino community stronger than ever,â€ said NaFFAA President and Chairman Brendan Flores. â€œDiversity includes differences in sexual orientation, religion, political parties, and other groups you affiliate yourself into. We hope that instead of focusing on these differences, we will take time to focus on our biggest similarity - being Filipino-Americans.â€ Diverse Segments Director Gio Duaqui says: â€œApproximately 4.2 million Filipino Americans are working tirelessly to achieve the American Dream and to improve their communities. Imagine how much more we can accomplish and amplify our efforts as a unified voice by building bridges to other segments of our diverse population. I am proud to see NAFFAA is moving in that direction to ensure everyone is welcome and included. After all, the American Dream belongs to all of us. Happy Pride Month!â€ NaFFAA does not tolerate any forms of prejudice against any of our â€œkapatidâ€ in the LGBTQI+ community. We celebrate their successes and recognize the great and important contributions they make to make us a better and stronger country. Our leaders look forward to continuing to support our â€œkapatidâ€ in the LGBTQI+ community. See full press release here: https://naffaa.org/naffaa-celebrates-fil-am-leaders-in-the-lgbtq-community-for-junes-pride-month-celebration/ â€”- Since 1997, the National Federation of Filipino American Associations (NaFFAA) has been the standard-bearer for promoting the welfare and well-being of the four million Filipinos and Filipino Americans throughout the United States. NaFFAA is the largest non-partisan, non-profit organization and national affiliation of Filipino American institutions, umbrella organizations, and individuals. Its fourteen-member regions cover the continental United States, Alaska, Hawaii, and the Pacific Islands.

An activist and survivor, Tarana Burke created the phrase â€œMe Tooâ€ in 2006, over a decade before famous white actresses would remake it into a viral hashtag in their response to abuse perpetrated by Harvey Weinstein. Burke has worked to empower survivors for over three decades, was named alongside other women â€œThe Silence Breakersâ€ as Time Magazineâ€™s 2017 Persons of the Year, and is currently Senior Director at Girls for Gender Equity. Image Description: A graphic with a teal colored bar at the top with the words â€œBlack Women Led The Wayâ€, below left is a black and white drawing of Tarana Burkeâ€™s face, smiling. Next to that are the words: Tarana Burke, 1973 - present. Tarana Burke took her experiences of sexual violence and used her healing to help others, founding the Me Too movement and teaching "empowerment through empathy" - to show others that they are not alone.

When Clarence Thomas was nominated for a seat on the Supreme Court in 1991, Anita Hill made a report to the FBI that was subsequently publicized â€“ she then stood before Congress to testify that Thomas had sexually harassed her over a period of years while he was her supervisor. Despite many personal attacks on her reputation to discredit her story, Hill persisted. While Thomas was confirmed to the Supreme Court (though by the smallest margin in over a century), Hillâ€™s actions galvanized action on the issue of sexual harassment â€“ leading to federal laws allowing victims to seek restitution, a growing public understanding and support for change, and in 1992 a record number of women winning elections to Congress. Image Description: A graphic with a teal colored bar at the top with the words â€œBlack Women Led The Wayâ€, below left is a black and white photograph of Anita Hill holding a microphone, altered to look like a drawing. Next to that are the words: Anita Hill, 1956 - present. Anita Hill stood up against both a Supreme Court nominee and a culture of accepting harassment as the norm. Facing down personal attacks and disbelief, she drove policy changes and a new public understanding of this issue. Anita Hill image remix of photo by Gage Skidmore, CC BY-SA 3.0 <https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0>, via Wikimedia Commons

While residing in Beaufort County Jail in North Carolina in 1974, Joan Little was assaulted by a guard and killed him with the ice pick he had used to threaten her. Her trial was the first time that a woman was acquitted for using deadly force in resisting sexual assault. Littleâ€™s trial and the groundswell of support for her case changed attitudes around the use of self-defense in such cases, as well as bringing light to the racial and sexual inequalities in the criminal justice system and laid the foundation for reforms like the Prison Rape Elimination Act. Image Description: A graphic with a teal colored bar at the top with the words â€œBlack Women Led The Wayâ€, below left is a black and white line drawing of Joan Little. Next to that are the words: Joan Little, 1953 - present. Joan Little killed the jail guard who assaulted her in self defense, leading to a trial that would shine a light on the racism of the justice system and death penalty, and the power of movements to create change. Joan Little drawing by dignidadrebelde at https://flickr.com/photos/28987073@N08/30539190706,:=:https://www.flickr.com/photos/28987073@N08/30539190706, licensed under CC-BY-2.0

Towson University's Asian Arts & Culture Center, the DC South Asian Arts Council, and a team of artists, musicians, and creatives from the Baltimore and Washington, DC regions invite you to help tell stories of the regional South Asian diaspora. UM Asian American Alliance] On Jan 21st (Fri) at 10 am, you are invited to a vigil in memory of Mr. Yao Pan Ma. Join us to grieve with the Ma family and call for unity. Please meet at 175 East 125th Street, cross street 3rd Avenue, next to Salvation Army. Come join Harlem's residents, community organizations, and elected officials including Grace Meng, Alvin Bragg, Gale Brewer, and Mark Levine to recommit to unity. We will call for better safety where Mr. Ma was attacked and for that, we must redefine our mental health and criminal justice systems. We also call for more social services throughout the city for vulnerable people, including seniors and the homeless population. To truly honor Mr. Ma, let people of all races work together to create a safer and fairer New York. PLEASE HELP BY: (1) Repost and retweet on social media (2) Bring white flowers and white candles (3) Donate to this event or signup to volunteer with UM Asian American Alliance] Your support is a great solace for the grieving family and to our growing Asian senior population in Harlem. For more information, write to Upper Manhattan Asian American Alliance at uppermanhattanaaa@gmail.com
